Record.CAVI-Lemma: Fr. of RF calyx krater. From Athens. Unattributed. Last quarter fifth. 420-410.
Record.CAVI-Subject: A: Birth of Dionysus: Zeus seated; Dionysus emerging from his thigh; a hand holding a cloth to receive him (Hermes? Eileithyia?).
Record.CAVI-Comments: Found with about 400 frs. in a private house in Athens: dump of a potter's workshop, many, but not all, by the Painter of the Athens Dinos (Greifenhagen; see ARV[2], p. 1180). This fr. is not listed as by this painter. Kappa miswritten.
Record.CAVI-Footnotes: {1} in white. The first two letters also lightly incised [inscription in preliminary sketch?] (CVA).
Record.AVI-Bibliography: Philippart (1930), 19/22, fig. 2. — Greifenhagen (1931), n. .... — Trendall (1934), 176/2, fig. 1. — Greifenhagen (1935), 417 n. — A. Greifenhagen, CVA Bonn 1, Germany 1 (1938), pl. 33,9.

Record.CAVI-Lemma: Fr. of calyx or bell krater. Kleophon Painter. 430-420.
Record.CAVI-Subject: Dionysus with maenads and a satyr.
Record.CAVI-Comments: Done from AttScr and Matheson. I consider Oinothrophos a satyr name, but K.-D. has it as the name of a maenad, referring to RE, s.v. Oinotropoi, females given the power by Dionysus to transform everything into wine (see Pape, s.v.). However G. Neumann apud K.-D. translates Oinotrophos `Wein bauend,' rightly. The word appears here with assimilation.
